ABUJA – The Federal Government said it has trained 1,376 civil servants drawn from 48 Ministries, Departments and Agencies(MDAs) between November 2020 to December 2021 on e-government. Kashifu Inuwa Abdullahi, Director General of National Information Technology Development Agency (NITDA) revealed this on Tuesday in Abuja at the Champions Day/ Closing of 2021 Service Wide Capacity Building Programme on e-Government. Abdullahi said in order to achieve vibrant digital economy, there was a dire need to build the capacity of civil servants that would drive and provide services to citizens and implement the e-Government Masterplan. Makinde Condoles With Family of Late Aide, Tijani Wase Greets Senate President, Lawan At 63 He explained that digital technologies have brought about unprecedented opportunities to drive efficiencies, enable automation and change how society interacts and engages in all facets of life. “The pace of change is advancing, as are citizen expectations, and globally, governments need to transform their operations to be more accessible, transparent, and accountable. “Apart from aligning to the global trend to move to E-Government, countries need a clear and defined agenda and supporting process to drive change and leverage technology,” he explained. Commenting on the plans for 2022, NITDA boss said the e-Government Training Centre was targeting to train more civil servants, commencing from executive capacity building for top-level decisions and policymakers such as Permanent Secretaries, Chief Executive Officers of parastatals, and legislative members, as well as starting capacity building for both Federal and State public servants outside Abuja. He noted that some of the benefits the training would provide to the civil servants include, “Recognising the opportunities e-government can bring and identify and prioritize where technology can be best applied to drive efficiencies, enable change and improve service delivery for citizens. POLL “Understanding and analysing where to apply technologies appropriately to enable a digital transformation that serves the Department and citizens as well as developing and implementing a ‘Channel Shift’ strategy to encourage citizens to take up and move to the most efficient e-enabled services It would be recalled that e-Government Training Centre is established in Abuja with the sole mandate of providing capacity-building component of e-Government Masterplan implementation for civil servants across the MDAs.